    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-15T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-15T22:00:00-05:00" n="759"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d759">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.932/21: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-16T10:00:00+07:00"
                            >May 16, 1944—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 16—7:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>857. Political Vice-Foreign Minister last evening volunteered to Counselor
                    information that Chinese draft treaty would be completed not later than month
                    hence (re our 777, May 4<note n="22" xml:id="d759fn22">Not printed.</note>).
                    When asked if draft would also be presented to British, Vice-Minister said that
                    was another question, but we could be assured that we would be “among the first”
                    to receive it.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
